Navigation project¶

This jupyter showcases the results of trying out several agents to solve the bananas environment (not provided in this repo).

What has been tried:

  • DQN and double DQN agents
  • with deep neural network and also duelling network architectures
  • with a Memory Buffer

What has not been tried:

  • prioritized experience replay. It is a work in progress in the code, the sampling itself is implemented but not the update rules and even the implementation is not good enough (the naïve approach is too slow)
  • the pixels environment

Also, this notebook does not show how to train an agent (only at the end), I take advantage of the runs that have been logged using mlflow.

The basis for the implementation has been the DQN code provided in the course repository. That implementation with the default parameters already solves the problem.

To run the code below, first we do the necessary inputs and general setup.

the cells in this notebook are meant to be run in order

Getting the results from the experiments¶

In every run the following parameters and metrics are logged using mlflow (only the relevant ones represented).

  • score
  • number of episodes to reach a solution
  • number of episodes trained
  • type of agent (DQN, DDQN)
  • underlying model (deep neural network, duelling neural network)
  • learning rate, epsilon, epsilon decay, etc.
  • model weights every 100 steps and in the final step (final model)

In mlflow, each execution is called a run and they can be grouped in experiments. And the different runs are grouped by experiments. In this case, I called the experiment bananas:

In [2]:

# Get everything that is discussed in this notebook in a DataFrame
scores_summary = pd.DataFrame()
for i, run in enumerate(runs):
    score = pd.DataFrame([ dict(m) for m in client.get_metric_history(run_id=run.info.run_id, key='score')])
    avg_100 = score['value'].rolling(100).mean()
    std_100 = score['value'].rolling(100).std()
    k2, p = stats.normaltest(score.value.iloc[-100:])
    row = {
        'run_id': run.info.run_id,
        'episodes_trained': len(score),
        'score_final': avg_100.iloc[-1],
        'score_final_std': std_100.iloc[-1],
        'solved': run.data.params.get('is_solved', 'False') == 'True',
        'normally_distributed': p > 0.05,
        'p_value': p,
        'success_probability': 1 - stats.norm(avg_100.iloc[-1], std_100.iloc[-1]).cdf(13),
        'epsilon_decay': float(run.data.params.get('epsilon_update_function decay decay_factor', 0.995)),
        'artifact': f'{mlruns_path}/{experiment.experiment_id}/{run.info.run_id}/artifacts/model_final.pkl',
        'training':run.data.tags['mlflow.runName'],
        'model': run.data.tags.get('qnetwork', 'QNetwork()').split('(')[0],
    }
    if run.data.params.get('is_solved', 'False') == 'True':
        step_solved = run.data.metrics['episodes_to_solve']
        row['episodes_to_solve'] = step_solved
        score_avg = score.loc[score.step<=step_solved, 'value'].rolling(100).mean().iloc[-1]
        row['score_to_solve'] = score_avg

    scores_summary = scores_summary.append(row, ignore_index=True)

Let's see all the runs¶

Before detailing what each run is, first let's plot all the runs (we'll see clusters of experiments)

In [5]:
def plot_runs(runs, title='Runs', legend=False):
    plt.figure(figsize=(18,10))
    x_lim = 0
    for i, run in enumerate(runs):
        try:
            score = pd.DataFrame([ dict(m) for m in client.get_metric_history(run_id=run.info.run_id, key='score')])
            color = cc.glasbey_bw[i % len(cc.glasbey_bw)]
            x_lim = max(x_lim, score.step.max())
            
            row = scores_summary.loc[scores_summary['run_id'] == run.info.run_id, :].iloc[0]
            plt.plot(score.step, score.value.rolling(100, min_periods=1).mean(), 
                     linewidth=2, color=color, alpha=0.8, linestyle='-', 
                    label=f"{row['training']} {row['model']} decay={row['epsilon_decay']}"
                    )

            if run.data.params.get('is_solved', 'False') == 'True':
                step_solved = run.data.metrics['episodes_to_solve']
                score_avg = score.loc[score.step<=step_solved, 'value'].rolling(100).mean().iloc[-1]
                plt.plot(step_solved, score_avg, marker='X', markersize=15, color=color)
        except MlflowException:
            pass
    plt.xlabel('Number of episodes')
    plt.ylabel('Average score for 100 last episodes')
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlim([0, x_lim])
    # plt.ylim([0, 18])
    if legend:
        plt.legend()
plot_runs(runs, title = 'Figure 1. Agent performance for every agent.')

A note on stopping criteria¶

The previous graphic shows:

  • the average score for the last 100 episodes for every run (lines)
  • an "X" mark when the average score reached 13 or - in other words - when the problem is solved

The "X" is not in the last episode. This is because the stopping criteria was not chosen as just solving the problem because, as it is seen, there is some margin for improvement. In the implementation, this is fully customizable because a function can be passed to the agent to let the agent know then it can stop training. In practice the agent stopped training when:

  • the number of episodes reached 2000
  • or when it was solved and the average score of the last 200 episodes is greater than the average score of the last 100 episodes

The second criteria looks for score stability in a dynamic way.

For reference, the code to train the agent looks like this:

agent = DQN_Agent(
    banana_environment,
    is_finished_function=[loggable(moving_average_cross, 100, 200), loggable(moving_average, 100, 13)],
    is_solved=loggable(moving_average, 100, 13),
    max_train_episodes=2000,
    epsilon_update=loggable(decay, 0.8, min_value=0.01),
    seed=0)
agent.train()

To see that this stopping criteria actually make sense, the following table and graphic shows that the average score after training is well above 13.

On failed experiments¶

Experiments where run looping through a grid of hyperparameters. The one that made some experiments fail was the decay factor for ε (epsilon). In every episode the agent chooses actions using the ε-greedy approach, with ε decaying exponentially from run to run.

In the implementation, the way of making ε is configurable when defining the agent. It was always chosen like with this function:

def decay(agent, decay_factor, min_value=0):
    agent.epsilon = max(agent.epsilon * decay_factor, min_value)
    return agent.epsilon

The following cross table shows whether the experiment was solved or not based only on the decay factor. 0.995 is the default value, that is why there are more experiments with that value.

A closer look at the agents¶

All of the agents above reached a good solution within a reasonable number of episodes. It is difficult to say which one is the best. We want the agents to have a good score because they are good, not because they are lucky or have a good run. That is why the success probability has been computed.

The success probability is the probability of an agent getting a score greater or equal than 13. This is calculated assumming that the score distribution of the last 100 runs is a normal distribution, which is not always true. The reason for this not being always true that I can think of:

  • extremely bad luck (highly unlikely)
  • the agent is not yet stabilized (its model weights)

Maybe another stop criteria could have been used.

  • The one that trained for the least amount of episodes

Which agent is the best?¶

To me, this one:

DQN agent with a duelling network architecture using an epsilon decay factor of 0.1.

I chose it because:

  • It got trained fast (341 episodes to solution, 639 in total)
  • Has a very high final score, 15.94. Not the highest though

It is also tempting to choose this one: Double DQN agent with a duelling network architecture using an epsilon decay factor of 0.4.

Because it has the highest chance of succeding and a very high score (16.64), but it did take a while to stabilize.

Future work¶

Some basics¶

  • Fix bugs
  • Implement prioritized replay
  • Try with the pixels environment. This requires a different network acrhitecture.
  • Study the effect of all the parameters that have been tried, for example the effect of increasing the t_every parameter. Several values were tried, but the results have not been fully analyzed. The same is valid for the decay factor.

Other ideas¶

  • The way of decaying ε as exploration-exploitation dicotomy can be done diferently. Using always zero (always exploit) does not stop the agent from learning. However it does look like exploring makes sense at the beginning and not at the end. Maybe an step function is better than exponential decay.
  • Explore other neural network configurations. It looks like for this environment smaller networks could work too.
  • Out of curiosity, get the agents that did not succeed in training and make them play with ε=0. My suspition is that they did learn to play, however because they were most of the time choosing actions at random they did not show it.
